INSERT INTO `field_data_body` VALUES ('node','blog',0,1,1,'und',0,'<p>While this article isn\'t strictly about development, any freelance developer will inevitably have to deal with clients and I therefore think this is a legitimate subject for discussion on this site.</p><p>Like a lot of freelance developers I get a lot of work through recruitment agents. I estimate that 70% of my work comes through agents and the remaining 30% is work for clients who have approached me directly either through <a href=\"http://www.systemick-web-development.co.uk\" target=\"_blank\">my business website</a> or from a personal recommendation. Strictly speaking, if I have found the work through a recruitment agent then the client is the recruitment agent and not the people/comapny for whom I am doing the work. For the purpose of this article, when I use the word client I am using it to refer to the comapny for whom I am doing the work.</p><p>Clients come in all shapes and sizes. Some are good and some indifferent. Occasionally you come across a bad one. I find that I much prefer working for a digital agency rather than any other type of company. You are working for people who have at least some understanding of the development process and therefore have realistic expectations about what can and can\'t be achieved within a given timescale. The culture in digital agencies is much more relaxed and developers tend to be treated with more courtesy and respect. You are usually working with a number of other developers with different skillsets from whom you can learn new skills and swap experiences.</p><p>I also have a slight preference for working in smaller agencies. I\'ve worked for one or two larger agencies where the atmosphere was slightly unfriendly. The atmosphere is usually friendlier and you get to meet people higher up in the chain of command. I worked for an agency recently that consisted of only five people. A conversation in their studio usually involved the whole company which made for a good working environment. My desk was just a few feet away from that of the MD and it was good to see how he worked at close hand.</p><p>I don\'t discount non agency work altogether but I have had bad experiences when I have done this type of work. I once walked out on a project on day two becasue the guy I was working for expected me to work longer hours at no extra cost to him. When I objected he became quite angry and despite the fact that I had told him before I started that I expected to be paid for any extra hours I needed to work. This is by no means typicaland there are good clients who are not digital agencies. My all time favourite client is a big London media company with over a thousand people working in the building and who\'s parent company was Time Warner. Sure, I didn\'t get to meet many of those thousand employees but the ones I did meet were good people and I\'m still in touch with them.</p><p>If I have any advice to give fellow freelancers it is to sort out as many of the details before you actually start work. This is especially true if you are working without a contract. At the very minimum you should get an email agreeing what your working hours and rate of pay should be. Most people are decent and honest but not everyone. It pays to be cautious.</p>','','full_html'),('node','blog',0,3,3,'und',0,'<p>Usually when I want to find a way of doing something in Drupal I just use Google. The great thing about using open source software is that when you need some advice on how to do something, inevitably someone has been there before you and posted a solution on the net. One of the reasons I wanted to start this blog was so that I would be able to contribute to this process. It is possible to learn a great deal about Drupal without ever having to open a book. Books on Drupal (and books on general programming) tend to be quite expensive. Coming from Yorkshire, I\'m usually reluctant to part with money and recommending that other people spend money on books doesn\'t come naturally to me. Books can however be very useful, particularly when you are starting out using something you know little or nothing about. I have read the three books listed below from cover to cover and they have served me well on my path to better Drupal development.</p><p>The first book about Drupal that I ever read was <a href=\"http://www.amazon.co.uk/Drupal-Development-Edition-Experts-Source/dp/1430228385/ref=sr_1_1?ie=UTF8&amp;qid=1349783834&amp;sr=8-1\" target=\"_blank\">Pro Drupal 7 Development</a> by John VanDyk and Todd Tomlinson.&nbsp;(It was D6 when I first read it). This is a great book for beginners and I\'d recommend it to anybody who is new to Drupal. It does however require a working knowledge of PHP. It covers all the major features include in Drupal core. For absolute beginners there are chapters on hooks, Drupal\'s menu system, users, nodes, fields, the database API, theming, blocks, taxonomy, the form API and the Drupal file system. There are also slightly more advanced chapters on caching, sessions, jQuery in Drupal as well as advice on how to writer secure code, development best practices and optimization.</p><p>A more thorough and comprehensive coverage is given by <a href=\"http://www.amazon.co.uk/Definitive-Guide-Drupal-Apress/dp/1430231351/ref=sr_1_1?s=books&amp;ie=UTF8&amp;qid=1349785326&amp;sr=1-1\">The Definitive Guide To Drupal 7</a> which is written by various authors.&nbsp;All the subjects covered in the previous book are included here but they are studied in greater detail and the author\'s assume more Drupal and programming experience. I once started work on a project only to discover that for reasons beyond my control, I wasn\'t able to get much further than installing Drupal and a couple of contributed modules before work was delayed. While I was clicking my heels waiting for it to resume I downloaded this book to my laptop and pretty much read it from cover to cover. It expanded my knowledge of Drupal a good deal. Not only is there comprehensive coverage of all the standard Drupal components but the book also contains chapters on Drupal Commerce, Drush, scaling Drupal and contributing back to the community. At over 1000 pages this is a serious read but if you are serious about learning Drupal the effort is well worth it.</p><p>The final book that I want to talk about is the most advanced of the three:&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.amazon.co.uk/Drupal-Module-Development-Matt-Butcher/dp/1849511160/ref=sr_1_1?s=books&amp;ie=UTF8&amp;qid=1349786102&amp;sr=1-1\" target=\"_blank\">Drupal 7 Module Development</a> which is again written by various authors.&nbsp;This book is targeted at experienced PHP developers and is therefore not recommended for everyone. This book took me to a whole new level and I believe it is a must for anyone wanting to earn a living writing custom modules. The first chapter is just a brief description of the various components that make up Drupal. After that you have chapters on creating custom modules, theming those modules, building admin interfaces, creating your own entities, security, node access and a great chapter on using jQuery and javascript in Drupal.</p><p>So there you have details about my three favourite books on Drupal. I\'m currently looking to improve my knowledge of jQuery and javascript in Drupal. I\'ve looked at <a href=\"http://www.amazon.co.uk/Drupal-JavaScript-jQuery-Matt-Butcher/dp/1847196160/ref=sr_1_1?s=books&amp;ie=UTF8&amp;qid=1349786908&amp;sr=1-1\" target=\"_blank\">Drupal 6 Javascript and jQuery</a>&nbsp;by Matt Butcher but I\'d prefer something specific to Drupal 7 as I rarely have to work with D6 these days. Can anyone recommend a good book.</p>','','full_html'),('node','blog',0,7,7,'und',0,'<p>I have another Drupal site (<a href=\"http://www.systemick-web-development.co.uk\">Systemick Web Development</a>) that I use to attract business. Though there is only one account on this site and there was only ever going to be one account I neglected to change the default registration setting from \'Visitors, but administrator approval is required\' under Admin &gt; Configuration &gt; People. This means that if they so desire, anyone can go and register for an account on the site but they will need admin approval for the account to be activated.</p><p>The site has been up a couple of years and I\'ve never seen any attempts to register a new account. I have Google Analytics on the site and I don\'t ever remember seeing any hits on the page user/register. There\'s a captcha on this page so only bots are unable to spam the form. Just recently things have changed. In the last week I\'ve had around 20 new users apply for accounts. I\'m scratching my head on this one. I can\'t think of any legitimate reason why these people would want an account on my business site so I\'m guessing it\'s some sort of attempt to hack into the site. \'But why\' is the question I\'m asking myself. What do they hope to achieve with an insignificant little site like mine? Don\'t these people have a life? Guess I should change the config setting to \'Administrators only\'. Ho hum.</p>','','full_html'),('node','blog',0,8,8,'und',0,'<p>&nbsp;</p><p>I saw a tweet from @Dries recently about Views becoming part of core in Drupal 8. Though this isn\'t definite yet there are a lot of people pushing for it and it wouldn\'t be a big surprise if it happens. I first read about the initiative to get Views into core back in May on <a href=\"http://www.angrydonuts.com/help-fund-views-in-core\" target=\"_blank\">Angry Donuts</a>.</p><p>The case for including Views in core is very strong. Views is the mother of all contributed modules. According to <a href=\"http://drupalmodules.com/top-downloads\">Drupal Modules</a> Views is&nbsp;the third most downloaded module but when you see that the first two are Admin Menu and CCK which are both part of core in D7 then you&nbsp;realise that it is probably the most downloaded module in D7. I actually can\'t remember the last time I built a Drupal site that didn\'t&nbsp;use the Views module. Whenever you look at a Drupal site and see a list of items you just assume that it will be a View because everybody&nbsp;does it that way.</p><p>Anyone who has ever looked at the code (not a small job as there is rather a lot of it) can\'t fail to be impressed with the quality of the&nbsp;object oriented PHP code. The ajax/js functionality in this module is second to none. Another impressive feature is the ease with which&nbsp;it is possible to write modules that hook into Views functionality. The twitter module is a great example of this. Installing the&nbsp;<a href=\"http://drupal.org/project/twitter\" target=\"_blank\">Twitter module</a> adds \'Twitter Message\' to the dropdown list of types of content that can be used in a View on the \'Add a new View\' page. This&nbsp;is a truly great module. If ever there was a module that deserves to be in Drupal core then this is it.</p><p>However I must admit to having mixed feeling when I read the Tweet. My reasons for this? Well I believe that Drupal core should be as lean&nbsp;as possible. I beleive that developers should have a choice of which modules to install. When I download D8 I don\'t want the overhead of&nbsp;having to download a lot of modules that I may not need. Keep Drupal lean is what I believe but that\'s only my opinion and I\'d love to hear&nbsp;yours. What do you think?</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p>','','full_html'),('node','tutorial',0,11,11,'und',0,'<p>Installing a new theme on a Drupal site is one of the simplest things you will ever do in Drupal. Drupal 7 comes with several themes included in core but I\'m going to show you how to download a theme from the Drupal website. I\'ve chosen to use the Touch theme developed by <a href=\"http://drupal.org/user/79351\" target=\"_blank\">ravi_9793</a> because it\'s the theme used on <a href=\"http://drupal-developer.co.uk\" target=\"_blank\">drupal-developer.co.uk</a><br /><br />Point your browser at the <a href=\"http://drupal.org/project/Themes\" target=\"_blank\">Drupal themes page</a>. Using the \'Filter by compatibility\'dropdown you can filter the results to show only D7 themes. At the time of writing the Touch theme is on the first page. Clicking on the theme title will take you to to the Touch page and from here you can download either a tar file (Linux) or a zip file(Windows) using the link at the foot of the page. Download this file and copy it to the folder sites/all/themes. You may need to create this directory if it doesn\'t yet exist. Once it is in there you should unzip/untar the file after which you should see a new touch directory.<br /><br />Next you need to log in as the admin user on your site and navigate to admin &gt; appearance. On this page you should see a list of themes. If you are using a new install and you are still using the default Bartik theme the central section of your page should look like the image below.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><img src=\"/sites/default/files/content/image1.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"940\" height=\"478\" /></p><p><br /><br />Under the Touch image click the link that says \'Enable and set default\' and the top section of you page should now look like this.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><img src=\"/sites/default/files/content/image2.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"940\" height=\"478\" /><br /><br /><br />Now if you navigate to the front page of your site you will see that the appearance has changed. If you have not yet added any content your page will look like the image below.<br /><br /><br /></p><p><img src=\"/sites/default/files/content/image3.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"940\" height=\"478\" /></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Your site is now installed.</p>','','full_html'),('node','tutorial',0,12,12,'und',0,'<p><em>All references to Drupal in this article refer to Drupal 6. In Drupal 7 CCK comes included in Drupal core so you don\'t need to download the modules mentioned in this tutorial. However the steps to install a module are the same in D7 as they are in D6.</em></p><p>Installing a new module is possibly the easiest thing you will ever need to do in Drupal. In this tutorial I am going to install the Content Construction Kit (CCK) module along with 3 other CCK modules that can be used to add different types of content onto a web page. These extra modules are FileField, ImageField and Link which means we will install 4 modules in all.</p><p>These modules allow site admins to create content types which site users can then use to create different types of content. They are used so often in Drupal 6 these days that all but the Link Module have been incorporated into Drupal 7 core and come with the default installation.</p><p>The Urls for these modules are here:</p><p><a href=\"http://drupal.org/project/cck\">http://drupal.org/project/cck</a><br /><a href=\"http://drupal.org/project/filefield\">http://drupal.org/project/filefield</a><br /><a href=\"http://drupal.org/project/imagefield\">http://drupal.org/project/imagefield</a><br /><a href=\"http://drupal.org/project/link\">http://drupal.org/project/link<br /></a><br />At the bottom of each of these pages is a number of links to download the required items. You can download a tarball (.tar.gz) or a zipped (.zip) file. Being a Linux user I usually opt for the tarball. Once you have downloaded these you should move them into the directory sites/all/modules and unzip them. If you have a new Drupal installation and this directory doesn’t yet exist you will need to create it. To unzip the tarball in Linux use the command&nbsp;<em>tar -xzvh tarball.tar.gz.</em>&nbsp;I usually delete the tarball after I have unzipped it. You should now have 4 directories within your modules directory.</p><p>The final step to allow you to start using these modules is to enable them. To do this you will need to log in as the administrator and navigate to Administer – Site Building – Modules. Here you should see a screen similar to the one below:</p><div id=\"attachment_50\" class=\"wp-caption alignnone\" style=\"width: 310px;\"><a href=\"http://systemick.files.wordpress.com/2011/04/screenshot-1.png\"><img class=\"size-medium wp-image-50\" title=\"Drupal Module Screen\" src=\"http://systemick.files.wordpress.com/2011/04/screenshot-1.png?w=300&amp;h=240\" alt=\"Drupal Module Screen\" width=\"300\" height=\"240\" /></a><p class=\"wp-caption-text\">Drupal Module Screen</p></div><p>Select all the check boxesin the CCK section, scroll down to the bottom of the page and hit the ‘Save Configuration’ button. You should now see a message telling you your configuration changes have been saved. That means your job is done. Your modules are now installed and you can start to use them to create new content types which your users can use to create new content.</p>','','full_html'),('node','tutorial',0,13,13,'und',0,'<p><em>This is a beginners tutorial that describes how to create a simple View</em></p><p>When I first started using Drupal and I was looking around on the web for articles and tutorials that would help me with the development that I was doing I noticed that a lot of people were talking about Views and the possibilities they offered. It took me a while to find out exactly what Views were for. I remember asking a colleague who had been using Drupal for around a year and being told that he still hadn\'t figured out exactly what Views were for. I spent quite a bit of time on Google trying to find out more but I could never manage to find a good explanation of what Views were for and it wasn\'t until I worked on sites that used Views that I was able to fully get my head around them.</p><p>The easiest way that I can explain them to you is that Views are really good for lists. You might need a list of nodes, comments, users or taxonomy terms on a page or within a block on your site and if that is the case, Views is very probably your best option. Lists of items are used on so many sites and I rarely work on a Drupal site that doesn\'t use Views. They are not currently part of Drupal core but it wouldn\'t be a big surprise if Views was included in core in Drupal 8. There\'s a discussion currently going on about this <a href=\"http://drupal.org/node/286665\" target=\"_blank\">here</a>.</p><p>When I created this site I used Views to display lists of recent tutorials both on a <a href=\"tutorials\">dedicated page</a> and within blocks on the front page. Here\'s how it\'s done.</p><p>First you need to <a href=\"content/installing-drupal-module\">download and enable the Views and Views UI module</a>. Navigate to Admin &gt; Structure &gt; Views and then click the \'Add new view\' link in the top left hand corner. You should see a form that looks something like the image below.&nbsp;</p><p><img src=\"/sites/default/files/content/views_creation_1.png\" alt=\"New View Page\" width=\"940\" height=\"494\" /></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>In the \'View name\' box enter a unique name for your View. Selecting the \'Description\' check box enables you to optionally add a description that will be displayed on the Views listing page.</p><p>The section below \'Description\' allows you to select what you want to include in your list. The first dropdown displays a list which includes content, comments, users and taxonomy terms. If you select content you are effectively displaying a list of nodes and you can restrict your list to a specified content type. When I needed to display a list of recent tutorials I selected the content type \'Tutorial\' (which I had created earlier) from this list. The next box allows you to restrict your list to only those nodes that are tagged with a specified term. If I had wanted to Show a list of tutorials about Views I could have used this box to filter out all other tutorials other than those tagged with the term \'Views\'. The final box in this section allows you to determine the order in which the tutorials were displayed. Because this was a list of recent tutorials it made sense to use the \'Newest first\' option.</p><p>The next section \'Create a page\' is enabled by default. To create a page to display your list keep the checkbox selected and enter a title for the page that you want to create together with a URL at which your page can be viewed. This section also allows you to choose how to format your list (I selected HTML List), choose wether you want to display the full tutorial, just a teaser or just the title, and wether or not to display links and comments.&nbsp;</p><p>Below this you can choose how many items you want to display on your page. If you want to display 10 items and there are more than 10 items in your list, you will most likely want to display pagination links on your page to allow users to click through to the next page. In this case you should select the \'Use a pager\' checkbox. You will most likely want your page to be linked to in a menu somewhere so you should select the \'Create a menu link\' checkbox and then choose a menu from the list that is displayed when the checkbox has been selected. You can also create a separate page on your site to display your list as an RSS feed by selecting the \'Include an RSS feed\' checkbox and entering the URL for your RSS page in the box that appears when the checkbox is selected.</p><p>By default Drupal will not create a block for your list but you can do this by selecting the \'Create a block\' checkbox. The box that appears when the checkbox is selected give you options for your block that are similar to those for the page.&nbsp;</p><p>If you need to make more adjustments to your View, for example, adding more filters &nbsp;or sort criteria you can do more editing by choosing the \'Continue &amp; edit\' button. As this tutorial is just an introduction to Views I\'m going to &nbsp;save that stuff for a later tutorial. By clicking the \'Save &amp; continue\' button you can create the View immediately. You should now be able to navigate to the page for your view and also, if you created a block your newly created block should appear in the page Blocks page at Admin &gt; Structure &gt; Blocks.&nbsp;</p>','','full_html'),('node','tutorial',0,14,14,'und',0,'<p>A short tutorial on creating a block.</p><p>Creating a block is possibly the simplest thing that you will ever do in Drupal. In fact itis so simple that it hardly warrants a tutorial but as it is a task that is so common in Drupal I decided to publish this tutorial.</p><p>Navigate to Admin &gt; Structure &gt; Blocks and click the \'Add block\' link in the top left hand corner. You will see a form that looks something like the one below.</p><p><img src=\"/sites/default/files/content/block_creation_1.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"940\" height=\"528\" /></p><p>In this form, enter a title, description and body text for the block that you need to create. If you have <a href=\"content/installing-drupal-module\">downloaded and installed</a> the WYSIWYG module you will be able to add images, links etc to the body. If not you will only be able to enter text.</p><p>Next you need to scroll down to the section of the form entitled \'REGION SETTINGS\'. The first item in this section will be a drop down list marked \'yourthemename (default theme)\'. This dropdown provides a list of regions within your theme. If you look at the file sites/all/themes/yourthemename/page.tpl.php you will see that it prints out the contents of these regions. A line of code that says \'print $page[\'sidebar_first\']\' will print out the contents of the sidebar-first region. To get your block to display in this region you have to add it to the region. Select the \'First Sidebar\' option from the dropdown.</p><p>In the final section on this page you can configure the visibility settings. By selecting options from the tabs on the left of this section you can configure your block to only appear when certain conditions apply. You can for example restrict your block to only be displayed when certain content types are displayed or when certain types of user are viewing the page. If you select the \'Pages\' tab you can enter a URL in the box, then select the \'Only the listed pages\' radio button you can restrict your block to only display on one page on the site. If you wanted to the block to display on all pages under the \'content\' URL you could enter \'content/*\' in the box. By entering &lt;front&gt; you could cause the block to only be displayed on the front page of the site.</p><p>Leaving all these options with their default settings will cause the block to appear on all pages of the site.</p><p>Once you have configured your block you should save it. It should then display on the parts of the site that you have configured it to appear on.</p>','','full_html'),('node','tutorial',0,15,15,'und',0,'<p>I know from past experience that there isn\'t a fantastic amount of material out there on the web for Drupal newbies and when I started doing Drupal I had to resort to buying the book \'Pro Drupal Development\' by John K. VanDyk. I have to say that this is an excellent book for beginners and I highly recommend it to you. I do realise however that its not everyone that wants to pay out their hard earned cash so I thought I\'d put this tutorial together</p><p>The first thing you need to do is download the source code.</p><p>wget http://drupal.org/files/projects/drupal-x.x.tar.gz</p><p>If you\' are not comfortable using the command line you can download the source code from <a href=\"http://drupal.org/project/drupal\" target=\"_blank\">http://drupal.org/project/drupal.</a></p><p>You should unpack the the source code into the directory that acts as your webserver root using the tar command. If your version of Drupal was 6.19 you would use the command</p><div>tar -zxvf drupal-x.xx.tar.gz</div><div>&nbsp;</div><div>Obviously you should substitute the version of Drupal you have downloaded for x.xx above.</div><div>&nbsp;</div><div>Drupal needs a database to be able to function. First you will need to create an empty database and then an account that will run your Drupal installation. If you use phpMyAdmin this is fairly easy to do. Personally I prefer to do it via the mysql command line client. The commands will vary according to which version of mysql you are using but will look something like this</div><div>&nbsp;</div><div><div>INSERT INTO `user` VALUES(\'127.0.0.1\',\'drupal_user\',password(\'mypassword\'),\'N\',\'N\',\'N\',\'N\',\'N\',\'N\',\'N\',\'N\',\'N\',\'N\',\'N\',\'N\',\'N\',\'N\',\'N\',\'N\',\'N\',\'N\',\'N\',\'N\',\'N\',\'N\',\'N\',\'N\',\'N\',\'N\',\'N\',\'N\',\'\',\'\',\'\',\'\',0,0,0,0);</div><div>&nbsp;</div><div>INSERT INTO `db` VALUES (\'%\',\'drupal\',\'drupal_userr\',\'Y\',\'Y\',\'Y\',\'Y\',\'Y\',\'Y\',\'N\',\'N\',\'Y\',\'Y\',\'Y\',\'Y\',\'N\',\'N\',\'N\',\'N\',\'N\',\'N\',\'N\');</div><div>&nbsp;</div><div>You will also need to run the \'flush privileges\' command for the 2 lines above to work.</div><div>&nbsp;</div><div>After you have created the database and account you should return to your unpacked Drupal installation and navigate to the directory &nbsp;drupal-6.19/sites/default. In this directory you will find the file default_settings.php. You should copy this file and call it settings.php. You should then change the permissions on this file so that it is writable by the web server. In Ubuntu this user would be www-data</div><div>&nbsp;</div><div><div>After you have created the database and account you should return to your unpacked Drupal installation and navigate to the directory &nbsp;drupal-6.19/sites/default. In this directory you will find the file default_settings.php. You should copy this file and call it settings.php. Once this is done you will need to open this file in your favourite editor and find the line that defines the variable $db_url and then change it so that it reflects the new database and account that you created earlier. In my example this would look like this:</div><div>&nbsp;</div><div>$db_url = \'mysql://drupal_user:my_password@localhost/drupal\';</div><div>&nbsp;</div><div>&nbsp;</div><div>Insert_priv</div><div>&nbsp;</div><div>Update_priv</div><div>&nbsp;</div><div>Delete_priv</div><div>&nbsp;</div><div>Create_priv</div><div>&nbsp;</div><div>Drop_priv</div><div>&nbsp;</div><div>During the install process Drupal will also attempt to create a directory at sites/default/files to store any files you upload for content in. You must ensure that your web server has write permissions in the sites/default directory for this to happen.</div><div>&nbsp;</div><div>If the install script succeeds, you will be directed to the \"Welcome\" page, and you will be logged in as the administrator already. You should see something like the screenshot below.</div><div>&nbsp;</div><div><img src=\"/sites/default/files/content/drupal_installation_1.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"940\" height=\"477\" /></div></div></div><div>&nbsp;</div><div>&nbsp;</div><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p>','','full_html'),('node','tutorial',0,16,16,'und',0,'<p>Content types (sometimes referred to as node types) are a way of categorizing different types of content in Drupal. To give an example - if you were creating a website for a car dealer you would probably want to display a page containing info about each vehicle that the dealer had for sale. In order to do this you would first need to create a content type for a vehicle which would contain fields for adding say, a manufacturer name, a model name, a registration number and a description as well as a field containing an image of the vehicle. In order to create these pages you would need to create nodes but before you could do that you would need to create a content type that would define what data a vehicle node could contain.</p><p>Creating a content types is another task that is so easy in Drupal CMS that it hardly warrants a full tutorial. Navigate to Admin &gt; Structure &gt; Content Types and click the \'Add new content type\' link on the top left of the page. You will see a form that should look something like the image below.</p><p><img src=\"/sites/default/files/content/content_type_creation_1.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"940\" height=\"494\" /></p><p>Enter a name/title for your content type in the boxes provided. Once tis is done you can configure the default behaviour for nodes of your new content type by selecting the tabs in the bottom left of the page. Here you can set wether or not a nodeis published automatically when it is created, wether or not comments are allowed and wether or not to add a link to one of the Drupal menus whenever a new node is created.</p><p>Once you are done on this page you will most likely want to add extra fields so you should hit the \'Save and add fields\' button at the foot of the page. You should arrive at a page that looks like this:</p><p><img src=\"/sites/default/files/content/content_type_creation_2.png\" alt=\"\" /></p><p>To add a new field you will need to enter a name for it in the box provided. You can then select a field type from the drop down list. The types are fairly self-explanatory. Using the same vehicle example from above, a model name would be a text field, a picture of the vuehicle would require an image field. Selecting a field type enables the widget field immediately to the right. Select a widget type then hit \'Save\'.</p><p>Now when you click the \'Add content\' link on the admin toolbar your new content type should appear in the list that appears on the page. Clicking the link for your content type will allow you to create a node of type &lt;your_new_content_type&gt;.</p>','','full_html'),('node','tutorial',0,17,17,'und',0,'<p>When I built this site I wanted to get it up and running in as little time as possible so I decided it might be a useful exercise to try and build a Drupal site without writing any code. I set myself the goal of creating a site in less than a day in which the only code would be code contained within modules and themes downloaded from <a href=\"http://drupal.org\" target=\"_blank\">drupal.org</a>. There would be no custom code whatsoever in my new site. I was by no means sure that this could be done but if I managed it, I could prove what a great CMS Drupal really is as well as making myself feel like a true Druplista. As it turned out I did have to cheat slightly but more on that later.</p><p>I wanted to build <a href=\"http://www.drupal-developer.co.uk\">drupal developer</a> so that I could share my thoughts about all things Drupal. I wanted to be able to write a blog as well as be able to display my posts on <a href=\"http://twitter.com/systemick\">twitter</a>. &nbsp;I also wanted to be able to provide some tutorials. I\'ve read hundreds of Drupal tutorials this last couple of years and most of them have been really helpful. I wanted to be able to give something back to the community and help newcomers in the same way that the community has helped me.&nbsp;</p><p>There would need to be a page on the site for each blog/tutorial and a way of tagging each of these with relevant terms. Commenting on these pages would be required functionality. There would also need to be pages where where users could view a complete list of blogs and tutorials. Finally the front page would need to display a list of recent posts together with blocks showing the most recent blogs and tutorials, a block showing my recent tweets, a block showing a little info about me and a block showing the most popular tags used on the site.</p><p>The first thing I looked at was the look and feel of the site. I wanted to use one of the themes on <a href=\"http://drupal.org\" target=\"_blank\">drupal.org</a> but using the default themes that come with Drupal core seemed too much like the easy option. When I went to the <a href=\"http://drupal.org/project/Themes\" target=\"_blank\">Drupal themes</a> page and filtered for Drupal 7 themes I was pleased to see that, at the time there were 315 themes available. The last time I looked, D7 was still relatively new and there wasn\'t nearly so many on there. \'Simple but elegant\' was what I was looking for and it didn\'t take me long to find <a href=\"http://drupal.org/user/79351\" target=\"_blank\">ravi_9793\'s</a> excellent <a href=\"http://drupal.org/project/touch\" target=\"_blank\">Touch theme</a>. Installing a theme is relatively simple but there\'s a link to a brief <a href=\"content/installing-drupal-theme\">tutorial</a>.</p><p>After the theme was installed I got to thinking about the different types of content needed on the site. I realised that there would be 3 types: tutorials, blog items and tweets. As they wouldn\'t be created within the site, tweets are kind of a special case. More on those later. For the others I created two new content types. Here\'s a <a href=\"content/create-content-type\">tutorial</a>&nbsp;explaining how to do this. I could have just used the default \'Page\' or \'Article\' content types but I always prefer to use my own when building a site. I could have used the same content type for both types of content but it makes life much easier later on in the build to use two distinct types. Any images added within blogs/tutorials would be embedded within the body field. For this I downloaded my first contributed module, the <a href=\"http://drupal.org/project/wysiwyg\" target=\"_blank\">wysiwyg module</a>. Here\'s a <a href=\"content/installing-drupal-module\">tutoria</a>l&nbsp;explaining how to install a module. After the install I navigated to Administration &gt; Configuration &gt; Content authoring - Wysiwyg profiles, clicked on \'Installation&nbsp;Instructions\', followed the instuctions to download and install the TinyMCE editor after which I selected the editor in the drop down lists for \'Full HTML\' and \'Filterred HTML\'. Once this was done Drupal added a wysiwyg editor to every body field when I was creating and editing content.</p><p>As I wanted to be able to add tags to each piece of content I needed another extra module. I downloaded and enabled the <a href=\"http://drupal.org/project/entityreference\" target=\"_blank\">entityreference module</a>. I then added a vocabulary in the form of a new term reference field to each of my content types. Here\'s a <a href=\"content/add-term-reference-field-content-type\">tutorial on how I did this</a>. Choosing the \'Autocomplete term widget\' allowed me to enter a comma separated list of terms whenever I create or edit content.&nbsp;</p><p>To be search engine friendly, I wanted all the URLs for blogs and tutorials on the site to be descriptive rather than just the default URL of node/&lt;nid&gt;. When creating content in Drupal the path module (which is part of Drupal core) enables users to create URLs that are search engine friendly. On the bottom of the node form is a tab for \'URL path settings\'. On this tab you can enter a search engine friendly URL for each piece of content. Better still, if you download and enable the <a href=\"http://drupal.org/project/pathauto\" target=\"_blank\">pathauto module</a>&nbsp;Drupal will fill in this field automatically. Not functionality that everyone requires but it suited me just fine.&nbsp;</p><p>Next up I started thinking about the front page. The default front page will display the 10 most recently created pieces of content. This number can be configured by navigating to Administration &gt; Configuration &gt; Site Configuration but I left it at 10. As I also wanted to be able to show lists of recent blogs and tutorials in blocks, I decided the simplest way to do this would be to use a View. I downloaded and enabled the <a href=\"http://drupal.org/project/views\" target=\"_blank\">Views module</a> and created views for the 10 most recent blogs and the most recent tutorials. Because I had used different content types for each of these, this was really easy to do. You can find a tutorial on <a href=\"content/create-view\" target=\"_self\">how to create a view</a>&nbsp;here. I added a block to each of these views so that when I went to Administration &gt; Structure &gt; Blocks I could see these blocks listed and add them to the \'Second Sidebar\' region. Here\'s a tutorial on how to <a href=\"content/create-block\">configure a block</a>.&nbsp;</p><p>While still on this page I added a custom block titled \'About Me\'. Clicking the \'Add Block\' link allowed me to enter the title and content of this block. Saving the block and adding it to the \'Second Sidebar\' region made it display on the front page. I also added the \'Search Form\' block to this region. Note that on this page, dragging the blocks using the cross on the left of the page allows you to determine the order in which they are displayed. Clicking the \'configure\' link allows you to specify that they only appear on certain pages. In my case I only wanted them on the front page. By clicking \'configure\' then the \'Pages\' tab, selecting the \'Only the listed pages\' option and entering &lt;front&gt; in the textarea I was able to accomplish this.</p><p>Creating these 2 views meant that I was also able to create the pages that display full lists of blogs and tutorials. The <a href=\"content/create-view\">views tutorial</a>&nbsp;explains how to create a URL to turn the default view into a page on your site and this is exactly what I did on Drupal Developer. To add these new pages to the main menu at the top of the page I edited the main menu. Here is a tutorial about <a href=\"content/create-menu-link\">creating menu items</a>.</p><p>Next I needed to add a block containing a list of the most popular tags on the site. For this I used the <a href=\"http://drupal.org/project/tagadelic\" target=\"_blank\">Tagadelic module</a>. When this module is enabled it creates a block for every vocabulary on the site. Navigating to Administration - Structure - Blocks I added a block for the default \'Tags\' vocabulary (the one I had added as an autocomplete text field to each of my content types) to the \'First Sidebar\' region.</p><p>I mentioned earlier that I wanted to put my tweets on the site. As tweets are retrieved from <a href=\"http://twitter.com\" target=\"_blank\">Twitter</a> they are slightly different to the rest of the content. Once again there is a contributed module that does all the leg work so I downloaded and enabled the <a href=\"http://drupal.org/project/twitter\" target=\"_blank\">twitter module</a>. Once it is enabled I was able to navigate to Administration &gt; Configuration &gt; Web services &gt; Twitter and check the box that says \'Import and display the Twitter statuses of site users who have entered their Twitter account information.\' Once this was done it was possible for any registered user to enter the details of their Twitter account when editing their account details. While logged in I clicked the \'Hello &lt;username&gt;\' link in the top right of the page, then on the \'Edit\' tab on the next page and then after clicking the \'Twitter accounts\' button I added my Twitter name in the box provided. To be able to import all my tweets I had to do a little extra work. I needed to download the Twitter rest API from github&nbsp;<a href=\"https://github.com/juampy72/twitter-rest-php/downloads\" target=\"_blank\">here</a>. This comes as either a zip or tar file. Inside is a php file - twitter.lib.php. I put this file in the directory sites/all/libraries/twitter/. This isn\'t an existing directory so I had to create it. To check that all my tweets had been imported I went back to the page where I edit my account details and clicked on the \'Twitter\' tab in the top right of the page. All my tweets were listed on this page so I was good to move on to the next step. In order to add a \'Recent Tweets\' block to the front page I had to create a view with a block. You can see from the diagram below that a new \'Twitter message\' item has appeared in the Content dropdown on the \'Add a new view page\'. I used this option and followed the steps in the content/create-view to create a view with a block which I then added to the \'Second Sidebar\' region.</p><p><img src=\"sites/default/files/content/site_from_scratch_1.png\" alt=\"A view of tweets\" width=\"940\" height=\"528\" /></p><p>I wanted site users to be able to contact me personally and as I don\'t particularly like receiving lots of emails for viagra I decided against putting an \'email me link\' somewhere on the site. Instead I opted to use the contact module which comes as part of Drupal core but is not enabled by default. Enabling this module causes a \'Contact form\' link to appear in the admin toolbar at the top of the page when logged in. Clicking this link took me to a page where I was able to configure a site wide contact form. I then added a link for the contact page to the main menu.</p><p>On other sites that I have worked on I have noticed that forms on a site tend to be abused. When I first set up a site for my business <a href=\"http://www.systemick-web-development.co.uk\" target=\"_blank\">Systemick</a>&nbsp;I noticed that fifty percent of the people using the site were attempting to use the comment forms to post spam messages on the site. Don\'t these people have anything more interesting to do with their lives? Did they imagine that I would allow comments to appear on the site without moderating them first? I wanted to prevent this on Drupal Developer so I used the <a href=\"http://drupal.org/project/captcha\" target=\"_blank\">captcha module</a>. Enabling this module allowed me to intoduce Captcha challenges to any of the forms on the site. You will notice that all the comment forms and the contact form have a captcha field on them. This saves lots of time spent moderating and deleting spam comments.</p><p>So there it is. That\'s how the site was created. It was done in slightly less than a day but as I admitted earlier I did cheat, because I did add a tiny bit of my own code. I wanted the front page to be 3 columns but I didn\'t want the traditional left and right sidebars. Instead I wanted the 2 sidebars to appear to the right of the main page so I had to edit my page.tpl.php template. I also needed to tweak the CSS file a little to get the exact display that I needed. Finally I had to edit my template.php file to add a title to the front page. Correct me if I\'m wrong but I couldn\'t find any other way to add a title.&nbsp;</p><p>However,if I\'d really wanted to I could have ommitted all these steps. I could have created a &nbsp;site without writing any code, in less than a day. Maybe a beginner couldn\'t do it quite as quickly as this but it does demonstrate what an awesome CMS Drupal really is. The great thing about Drupal is the fact that it is open source. Not only does this make it free of charge, it also means that there is loads of stuff about it on the web. If a beginner ever gets stuck, they can be fairly certain that someone else will have been in a similar situation prior to them and to have posted an answer either on <a href=\"http://drupal.org\" target=\"_blank\">drupal.org</a> or somewhere else on the web. A quick look at Google will provide an answer. Though there is a fairly steep learning curve when using Drupal, an internet connection and a little patience will enable someone with zero programming knowledge to build a working website.</p><p>&nbsp;</p>','','full_html'),('node','tutorial',0,18,18,'und',0,'<p>Adding a term reference field is a great way of tagging your content. Before creating a term reference field you will need to download and&nbsp;enable the <a href=\"http://drupal.org/project/entityreference\" target=\"_blank\">Entity Reference module</a>. You can fins out how to do this <a href=\"content/installing-drupal-module\">here</a>.</p><p>Before creating a term reference field you will need to create a vocabulary. Navigate to Admin &gt; Structure &gt; Taxonomy &gt; Add vocabulary andenter a name and descritption. Your new vocabulary will appear in the list and you can use the \'add terms\' link to add tags to your new&nbsp;vocabulary.</p><p>Go to Admin &gt; Structure &gt; Content Types &gt; Add content type and create a new content type. Add a field to your content type and from the&nbsp;\'Select a field type\' dropdown list select \'Term Reference\'. From the next dropdown list you should have the option of using either check&nbsp;boxes or an autocomplete widget. If you\'re using a large vocabulary you will probably prefer to use the autocomplete widget. Click the save&nbsp;button and you will see another dropdown list which will contain a list of the vocabularies on your site. Select your desired vocabulary.&nbsp;Click \'Save field settings\' and on the next page you can change some further settings for your new field. Click \'Save field settings\' again&nbsp;and you have successfully created your term reference field.</p>','','full_html'),('node','tutorial',0,19,19,'und',0,'<p>Navigate to Admin &gt; Structure &gt; Menus and you should see the screen below.</p><p><img src=\"/sites/default/files/content/menu_link_1.png\" alt=\"\" /></p><p>&nbsp;<img src=\"sites/default/files/content/menu_link_1.png\" alt=\"List of menus\" width=\"940\" height=\"528\" /></p><p>From here you can add a new menu if you need to or you can add a menu item to an existing menu. To add an item to the main menu click the \'add link\' corresponding to the Main Menu row. You should now see the screen below.</p><p><img src=\"sites/default/files/content/menu_link_2.png\" alt=\"Add a menu link to the main menu\" width=\"940\" height=\"538\" /></p><p>The settings on this page a fairly self explanatory. You should enter a path that your link will point to and adding a description is good for SEO purposes. You can disable your link if you don\'t want to put it live immediately. Select the menu item that you need as it\'s parent and by adjustiong the weight you can manipulate the order in which links appear in your menu. Click \'Save\' and you have added your menu item to the main menu. If enabled it should appear in your site\'s main menu.&nbsp;</p>','','full_html');
